node.contents: Is it OK to use == on enums in Java, or do I need to use .equals()? In my testing, == always works, but I'm not sure if I'm guaranteed of that. In particular, there is no .clone() method on an enum, so I don't know if it is possible to get an enum for which .equals() would return a different value than ==.

node.contents: However, the enum construct gives you various benefits:

astNode.text: However, the enum construct gives you various benefits:

node.contents:
• Each instance's toString() prints the name given in code.
  • (As mentioned in another post,) a variable of the enum type can be compared against constants using the switch-case control structure.
  • All the values in the enumeration can be queried using the values field that is 'generated' for each enum type
  • Here's the big one w.r.t identity comparisons: enum values survive serialization without cloning.

• Each instance's toString() prints the name given in code.
  • (As mentioned in another post,) a variable of the enum type can be compared against constants using the switch-case control structure.
  • All the values in the enumeration can be queried using the values field that is 'generated' for each enum type
  • Here's the big one w.r.t identity comparisons: enum values survive serialization without cloning.

node.contents: The serialization is a big gotchya. If I were to use the code above instead of an enum, here's how identity equality would behave:

node.contents: Encapsulating logic within enums using abstract methods is the real power of enums. It makes your code much more robust; when you add a new enum value in the future, the compiler will force you to implement the relevant logic, you don't have to remember to add a case to multiple switch statements.

node.contents: An even better way of doing it is to put the functionality within the enum itself, so you could just call roundingMode.round(someValue). This gets to the heart of Java enums - they're object-oriented enums, unlike the "named values" found elsewhere.

astNode.text: EDIT: The spec isn't very clear, but section 8.9 states:

node.contents: The body of an enum type may contain enum constants. An enum constant defines an instance of the enum type. An enum type has no instances other than those defined by its enum constants.

node.contents: == compares the references of two objects. For enums, it is guaranteed that there will only be one instance, and therefore for any two enums that are the same, == will be true.

elements.contents: public abstract class Enum<E extends Enum<E>> implements Comparable<E>, Serializable { // [...] /** * Returns true if the specified object is equal to this * enum constant. * * @param other the object to be compared for equality with this object. * @return true if the specified object is equal to this * enum constant. */ public final boolean equals(Object other) { return this==other; } }
